        public UByte lookUp(LookupTable lookupTable)
        Looks up this object in the given lookup table and returns the result. Considers this UByte as the address (left nibble as the row and right nibble as the column) and returns the corresponding UByte in the table as a new UByte. The table's data does not change after this operation.

        lookupTable - the given lookup table

      • subtractMod256M

        public UByte subtractMod256M(UByte inByte)
        Mutable subtracts this byte from the given byte and returns this byte. In fact this UByte will be added to the 2's complement of the given UByte. Example 1: 255 - 2 = 1111_1111 - 0000_0010 = 1111_1111 + (1111_1101 + 1) = 1111_1111 + 1111_1110 = 1_1111_1101 Note that the left-most bit will be truncated and the result will be 1111_1101 = 253. Example 2: 2 - 255 = 0000_0010 - 1111_1111 = 0000_0010 + (0000_0000 + 1) = 0000_0011 = 3 In fact, if the result is negative, it should be added to 256 and this means that the operations are being done in modulo 256.
        Parameters:
        inByte - the given byte
        Returns:
        this byte

      • subtractMod256

        public UByte subtractMod256(UByte inByte)
        Subtracts this byte from the given byte and returns this byte. In fact this UByte will be added to the 2's complement of the given UByte. Example 1: 255 - 2 = 1111_1111 - 0000_0010 = 1111_1111 + (1111_1101 + 1) = 1111_1111 + 1111_1110 = 1_1111_1101 Note that the left-most bit will be truncated and the result will be 1111_1101 = 253. Example 2: 2 - 255 = 0000_0010 - 1111_1111 = 0000_0010 + (0000_0000 + 1) = 0000_0011 = 3 In fact, if the result is negative, it should be added to 256 and this means that the operations are being done in modulo 256.
        Parameters:
        inByte - the given byte
        Returns:
        the result as a new object
